  1. PS1 revisited: Compare dep_time, sched_dep_time and dep_delay. It should be the case that dep_time - sched_dep_time = dep_delay. Does this hold? Be sure to use the new material you learned in this chapter. Explain your findings.

If you only took the difference of dep_time - sched_dep_time then you do not get dep_delay for various reasons. If the scheduled departure time is on the hour (e.g. 6:00 AM, 7:00 AM), then the difference between the two values uses 100 minutes instead of 60 minutes at 6:00 AM. For one observation, a plane took off early at 5:55 AM instead of 6:00 AM, but the calculated delay was -45 mins. Also, it does not take into account departure times that happen on a different day.

You can use functions from the lubridate package to create new dep time and scheduled time. But when you take the difference, it shows the results in seconds. You would need to either divide by 60 to get it in minutes like dep_delay or use another function that converts it.

clean_dttm <- function(year, month, day, time) {
  make_datetime(year, month, day, time %/% 100, time %% 100)
}
flights <- nycflights13::flights
(time_compare <- flights %>%
   filter(!is.na(dep_time), !is.na(sched_dep_time)) %>%
   mutate(
     dep_time_old       = dep_time,
     dep_time           = clean_dttm(year, month, day, dep_time),
     sched_dep_time_old = sched_dep_time,
     sched_dep_time     = make_datetime(year, month, day, hour, minute),
     dep_delay_clean    = dep_time - sched_dep_time,
     dep_delay_old      = dep_time_old - sched_dep_time_old
   ) %>%
    select(dep_time_old, dep_time, sched_dep_time_old, sched_dep_time, dep_delay, dep_delay_clean, dep_delay_old)
 )

  1. How does the average delay time change over the course of a day? Should you use dep_time or sched_dep_time? Why?

It appears as if the average delay increases over the course of a day, which makes sense as previously delayed flights impact subsequent flights the rest of the day. We plotted both dep_time and sched_dep_time, and it is clear that sched_dep_time should be used. As shown in Ch. 16 of R4DS, there is a bias in the actual departure times as humans often record times at “nice” intervals. Using the sched_dep_time will remove this bias from the data as shown in the graph.

# from Ch 16 of r4DS
flights_dt <- flights %>% 
  filter(!is.na(dep_time), !is.na(arr_time)) %>% 
  mutate(
    dep_time = clean_dttm(year, month, day, dep_time),
    arr_time = clean_dttm(year, month, day, arr_time),
    sched_dep_time = clean_dttm(year, month, day, sched_dep_time),
    sched_arr_time = clean_dttm(year, month, day, sched_arr_time)
  ) %>% 
  select(origin, dest, ends_with("delay"), ends_with("time"))

  1. Write a function that prints the mean of each numeric column in a data frame, along with its name.
means_df <- function(x) {
  num_cols <- Filter(is.numeric, x)
  mean_cols <- vector("list", ncol(num_cols))
  for (i in seq_along(num_cols)) {
    mean_cols[[i]] <- mean(num_cols[[i]])
    names(mean_cols)[[i]] <- names(num_cols)[[i]]
    cat(names(mean_cols)[[i]], ":", mean_cols[[i]],"\n")
  }
}

  1. In this question, we will investigate What happens when you use the map functions on vectors that aren’t lists. Use the following vector:
five_squares <- (1:5)^2
  1. Describe the output of using map on a list map(list(five_squares), rnorm). Explain why the output turns out this way.

The first argument in map is a list or atomic vector. Our list in this example is a list of 1 with five numbers, or [1:5]. When we use map and rnorm, the output provides a list of 1 with five numbers. Using map, this is equivalent to rnorm(1:5). This map is using the length of the list and passing it to the funciont, rnorm.

output_a <- map(list(five_squares), rnorm)

rnorm(1:5)
## [1]  0.3567948  0.1608803  1.3663077 -0.7116729 -1.0542075
  1. What does map(five_squares, rnorm) do? Why? In this code, the output goes through the function, rnorm, and passes the value in five_squares to the n argument. It does the first iteration of rnorm with n = 1, which is five_squares[1]. The next iteration goes to five_squares[2] so n = 2. So the number of observation changes each time. This example is different from (a) because it the first argument to the map function is the actual vector five_squares. Therefore, it passes its values not just the length of the list.
(output_b <- map(five_squares, rnorm))

  1. What does map(five_squares, rnorm, n = 5) do? Why? In this example, the number of observations has been defined as n = 5, which will not change in the iteration. In this map example, the values in five_squares are being used to define the output’s mean. By default, mean = 0, but in this example the mean will be the value in five_squares in each iteration. For example, five_squares[2] = 4, so the function becomes rnorm(n = 5, mean = 4). Typically when you use the map function, the vector/list is used on the first argument of the function. But in this example, the first argument has been defined (n = 5) so it goes to the next argument, which is the mean.
output_c <- map(five_squares, rnorm, n = 5)

  1. Next, propose a quantitative measure of traffic jam severity that combines the number of traffic JAM alerts with information in the subtype variable.

The quantitative measure: assign value for each jam based on the subtype of the jam: 1 for blank, 2 for “JAM_MODERATE_TRAFFIC”, 3 for “JAM_HEAVY_TRAFFIC”, 4 for “JAM_STAND_STILL_TRAFFIC” then sum them up with these weights and then take the square root of it.

  1. Plot this measure from 6AM-6PM CST. Is there any information that is conveyed by your severity measure that was not captured by plotting the number of jams? If so, what is it?

My severity measure take into consideration both how bad the traffic jams are and the number of jams and scale them to a reasonable level while just plotting the number of jams does not capture the severity of each jam.

severity <- 
  jams_bbox %>%
  mutate(jam_rank = ifelse(subtype == "JAM_STAND_STILL_TRAFFIC", 4 , ifelse(subtype == "JAM_HEAVY_TRAFFIC", 3 , ifelse(is.na(subtype), 1, 2)))) %>%
  group_by(scrape_dt) %>%
  summarise(severity = sqrt(sum(jam_rank, na.rm = TRUE)))

ggplot(severity, aes(x = ymd_hms(scrape_dt), y = severity)) + geom_col() + labs(x = "time")

#function
return_n_alerts <- function(id, datetime, lon, lat){ 
  waze %>% 
    filter(between(location_x, lon - 0.02, lon + 0.02) & between(location_y, lat - 0.02, lat + 0.02)) %>%
    filter(between(ymd_hms(scrape_dt), ymd_hms(datetime) - dhours(2), ymd_hms(datetime) + dhours(2))) %>%
    filter(type == "JAM") %>% group_by(scrape_dt) %>% summarise(n = n())
}
